s “samples” elements of Thornton’s art—and, occasionally, the author’s own story—to create “a biography in essays” that explores the life of its subject as a DJ might dig through a crate of records. Denise connects Thornton’s vaudevillesque performances in Sammy Green’s Hot Harlem Revue to the vocal improvisations that made “Hound Dog” a hit for Peacock Records (and later for Elvis Presley), injecting music criticism into what’s often framed as a cautionary tale of record-industry racism. She interprets Thornton’s performing in men’s suits as both a sly, Little Richard–like queering of the Chitlin Circuit and a simple preference for pants over dresses that didn’t have a pocket for her harmonica. Most radical of all, she refers to her subject by her given name rather than "Big Mama," a nickname bestowed upon her by a white man. It's a deliberate and crucial act of reclamation, because in the name of Willie Mae Thornton is the sound of Black musical resilience.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAfrican American women musiciansvBiography. 0aAfrican American women singersvBiography. 0aBlues (Music)xHistory and criticism. 0aWomen blues musicianszUnited StatesvBiography. 7aMUSIC / General.2bisacsh  aDJ Scholarship, Geo-musicology, Black popular music, Queer biographies, blues studies, folk scholarship, Southwest music history, mothering, Alabama, Houston, blueswomen, musical migrations, Hound Dog, Ball 'n' Chain, Peacock Records, American Folk Blues festival.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079782440uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/32118840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477327944423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477327944/original  a978-3-11-079782-4  University of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2023